## 3️⃣ `cleaned_data` — What It Is and Why It Exists

> 📒 **Interview note:** This is the most asked form question in interviews.

When a user submits a form, data arrives as **raw strings:**

```python
request.POST = {
    'title': '  My Post  ',    # raw string with extra spaces
    'age': '25',               # number, but as a string
    'email': 'JOHN@EMAIL.COM'  # email, but uppercase
}
```

After `form.is_valid()` runs, Django validates each field, converts values to correct Python types, and stores the result in `cleaned_data`:

```python
form.cleaned_data = {
    'title': 'My Post',        # spaces stripped ✅
    'age': 25,                 # converted to integer ✅
    'email': 'john@email.com'  # normalised to lowercase ✅
}
```

**Always use `cleaned_data` — never `request.POST` directly:**

```python
# ❌ Wrong — raw, unvalidated string
title = request.POST['title']

# ✅ Correct — validated and cleaned
title = form.cleaned_data['title']
```

